On the exterior, you see a husband, father and surgeon, but internally like many men, he was mentally on the edge of life, ready to jump. And sadly, those around never see this pain until they are planning our funerals. Thankfully he left encouraged to fight another day and promised he would call my psychotherapist. 

Men, trust me, I get it but please don’t jump. As I often say, you’re not tired of living, you’re tired of NOT living. So, comprehensively fight for what you deserve—you are more than a protector and provider—you’re human too.

It is written that if a man doesn’t work, a man doesn’t eat (2 Thess. 3:10). This is a true adage; however, if we never cease work in order to rest, work will rest us in peace. My brothers, we are worth more than our work!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Did you know that depression and a lack of rest are closely linked? A recent study by The Sleep Foundation revealed that 75 percent of people who have been diagnosed with depression also have trouble resting, falling asleep and/or staying asleep. Sleep issues also may contribute to the development of depression through changes in the function of the neurotransmitter serotonin. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
My brothers, we can keep saying we’re tired but until we do something about it, we will stay in a perpetual state mental fatigue. Always remember, no one will ever stop you from helping them do more work—so it’s up to you to stop grinding and start resting.
Countless good successful men have reached their mental edge and are one push away from falling off. So please, do not add unnecessary stress to the life of a man who is ready to jump.

For decades, repressed childhood trauma caused me to perceive every opposing opinion or minor altercation as disrespect and I quickly met it with an intemperate reaction. Instead of swatting away the mosquito, I’d wait for it to land on a glass table, then kill it with a sledgehammer — willing to risk it all to be heard . . . and to be right. 

As I share in Battle Cry, Emotional incarceration is a self-imposed mental imprisonment—when a man confines his “non-masculine” emotions and isolates his heart from the world. It appears to be a “safe space”; however, like the majority of real prisons in the world, this institution does not rehabilitate you. Instead, emotional incarceration breeds what got you sentenced in the first place—passive aggression, unresolved anger, and abandonment, to name a few.

Men, you can escape like I did but you must be courageous enough to face yourself — wage and win your internal battles before they become external wars!

Masculinity Is Not Toxic: Although women such as Harriet Tubman, Rosa Parks, and many female athletes have possessed masculine qualities, it is men who are pressured and confined to the limited definition of masculinity. As I share in Battle Cry, living as a human male becomes a relentless battle to only be the essence of strength and boldness. And when you don’t feel brave or strong, you are shamed for not being a “real” man. 

The battle between your heart (who you really are) and your mind (who you think you should be) intensifies as you struggle to conform. Then you become emotionally imbalanced. But it doesn’t have to be that way. The truth is, the Most High did not create some emotions for men and others for women. He created both genders human and all emotions for both genders!

Roman transparently shared that during some of his darkest times, my videos were a source of support and guidance — especially when his beloved father passed two years ago. He became teary-eyed as I intently listened to his heart. I encouraged him and we embraced before I left to prepare for my keynote.

It’s moments like these that make the hard, heart work with it! Roman, keep seeking our heavenly Father and He will provide earthly fathers to help guide you along this journey called life (Psalm 68:5).

You strain out a gnat (from your water) but swallow a camel.” We must do better. The youth will do what we do, before they do what we say.

For years, I held onto the belief that I possessed strong faith. However, it was only when I faced the arduous journey of caring for my mother through six long years of dementia that I came to understand that my faith was merely a theory. It wasn't until I embraced the testing of my faith that I was able to truly possess it (James 2:2-4).

Countless sunny days have slipped away from me in the past, simply because I failed to seize the joy and peace I experienced in those moments. In my book Battle Cry, I emphasize the importance of not letting our past traumas time travel and ruin our present. Instead, it is crucial to embrace and cherish “moments” of joy, peace, and happiness. By doing so, we can truly benefit from life’s blessings rather than being weighed down by its pressures.

By rejecting the notion of a “balanced life,” I experienced a profound transformation. I came to the realization that when we treat all things as equally important, our focus becomes fixated solely on work. It’s intriguing to note that the term “priority” originated in the 14th century, maintaining its singular form until the 20th century. Consequently, when we have “priorities,” we find ourselves relentlessly striving to accomplish an overwhelming number of tasks, rather than concentrating on what truly matters. This shift in mindset prompted me to reevaluate my approach and prioritize what holds genuine significance in my life.

Research reveals that ‘bad’ coaching can greatly impact children’s development negatively. When coaches neglect to confront their own unresolved anger and trauma, it can inadvertently affect young athletes. Engaging in psychotherapy has been shown to alleviate these detrimental effects, fostering an environment that supports the well-being of our children, mentally and athletically.

Please conduct thorough research on the coach before making any judgments and/or entrusting them with your child. Begin by searching the coach's name on Google and delve deeper into the available information. Look for references or testimonials that can provide insight into their coaching style and behavior. Additionally, watch videos of their interactions with youth to observe their demeanor and approach. It's crucial to pay attention to their personal character, particularly on social media platforms. If they openly express their thoughts and actions there, it is likely that they will exhibit similar behavior in real life and possibly more.

It was an honor to be invited by my brother, @DamianLillard to be a guest at Formula Zero (@frmlazro); a community of elite basketball players and coaches. Personally, being able to invest in enthusiastic, knowledge-hungry young athletes was a blessing — my heart truly needed this. I've always believed in the ability to teach character alongside champion-level skills, and this camp not only unequivocally affirmed a recent decision I made for my son but also instilled hope in me because:

1. You don’t need to condemn a player to coach them into becoming a champion.
 
2. By placing equal emphasis on character and performance, you cultivate champions both on the court and in life.

3. Yelling becomes a potent tool for encouragement when young men recognize your genuine concern for their personal growth beyond being just players.
 
4. It's possible to strongly challenge a player's stubborn will, teach them discipline, and still nurture their spirit without crushing it.

I could continue, but I'll conclude here. Parents, don't settle for less for your sons. There are still character coaches who develop well-rounded champions right here in America. I envision a future where Formula Zero becomes a coaching curriculum for compassionate men who aspire to guide boys into becoming comprehensive players and, in the process, transform themselves.

2.	Don’t Sweep It Under the Rug: Address issues as they arise instead of delaying or avoiding them.

3.	Empathy and Understanding: Try to see the situation from your spouse’s point of view. This can reduce defensiveness and open the way for more transparency.

As I sat in the car, my first thoughts were, “Oh, am I? Okay, let me go back to being merely a masculine male, one who suppresses his unresolved anger and trauma, then takes it out on those who had nothing to do with it.”

But immediately after processing those toxic thoughts, I made a vow that I would never return to the mental prison that holds more men captive than all the industrialized prisons in the world—emotional incarceration. And I kept that vow until I became a comprehensive man.

Men, just as we need to unlearn society’s limited definition of us, so do our women. Never forget that they have been programmed too. Remember, a divided house cannot stand; be patient with each other.

Video: @trippfontane on @tonightsconversation

Eighteen years ago, the Most High prompted me to pick up discarded pennies, representing my mission to uplift men deemed worthless by society. This penny, found underwater while cleaning my truck today, represents the many men drowning in despair.

Had it not been for my faith in Yahushua, combined with prayers for wisdom and the discipline to implement that wisdom, I could not have stayed afloat. I hope my story is proof that anyone can emerge from their abyss to a life of purpose and fulfillment.

In a world full of mixed intentions, the ability to see through facades is imperative. There are allies—those who pray and pull for you during the hardest rounds of life. Then there are the opportunists, those who prey and pull on you to exploit any opportunity for their gain; usually shadowed in false camaraderie. The wisdom to tell them apart isn’t just smart; it’s survival — protecting our well-being and guiding us in forming trustworthy relationships.

We are more than providers and protectors. The Most High created us to be comprehensive men… human beings, not human doings. A change for you to choose is coming soon… 

🎙️ @ronaldleejr

As we approach 2024, consider giving a life-changing gift. “Cry Like A Man” is more than a book; it’s a transformative tool for breaking free from emotional incarceration. It’s your opportunity to help yourself, a brother or friend unlock the life he deserves and take the first step on a journey that has liberated thousands of men!

Available on Amazon for $15 — order now and have it on New Year’s Day.

Embrace each new day, not merely New Year’s Day, as an opportunity for renewal and growth. Misconceptions about progress can be misleading; remember, even minimal progress signifies advancement. It’s crucial to recognize and celebrate these small victories (Zech 4:10). Free yourself from the relentless pursuit of performance; valuing oneself is as critical as achieving success. Never forget that with every triumph in life’s battles, we should not only grow stronger but be more thankful. Pursue your goals with diligence and determination, but never let the pursuit overcome you!

Beneath the ceaseless toil, every man yearns for a moment of peace—no one desires a life of unending work. But since our worth is often measured in our persistence, not our existence, and the affirmation we receive doesn’t extend beyond what we can produce, we keep pushing until a paramedic is pushing us. Men, let us redefine strength not as the endurance of ceaseless labor, but as the courage to embrace our worth beyond work, and to advocate for a world that values our being as much as our doing.

Our past is just that—the past—and it’s confined to that moment in time. However, when we allow our past traumas to time travel to the present, they influence our current existence. When I confronted my trauma with therapy and fervent prayer, a profound renewal of mind and heart followed, allowing space for forgiveness. This act liberated me from the traumatic chains of my past, opening the door for me to live in the moment for Yah, not my memories (Phil 3:13-14).

The power of a parenting lies not just in lovingly guiding our children, but also in acknowledging our own mistakes. A simple “I’m sorry” can heal, teach humility, responsibility and that every human has fallibility.
Fathers, keep your head up so that the spiritual war doesn’t choke you out! You are a warrior, even when it’s hard to believe… make no excuses (Gal 6:9) and keep fighting like one!
